  "prompt": "Is there any way to adjust title and font default settings in Google docs?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several ways to adjust title and font default settings in Google Docs:\n\n**1. Changing Default Styles (Recommended for consistent formatting):**\n\n   This is the most effective way to ensure your documents have a consistent look.  You can modify the default styles for Headings (Title, Heading 1, Heading 2, etc.) and Normal text.  Here's how:\n\n   *   **Modify Existing Styles:**\n       1.  **Format a Piece of Text:** Start by typing some text and formatting it exactly as you want your default *Title* or *Heading 1* (or any other heading).  This includes font, size, color, spacing, etc.\n       2.  **Select the Formatted Text:**  Highlight the text you just formatted.\n       3.  **Access the Styles Menu:** Go to `Format` > `Paragraph styles` > Choose the style you want to update (e.g., `Title`, `Heading 1`, `Normal text`).\n       4.  **Update the Style:** Select `Update [style name] to match`.  For example, `Update Title to match`.\n\n   *   **Apply Default Styles:**  Now, whenever you apply the 'Title' or 'Heading 1' style (or whichever you updated), it will automatically use your custom formatting.\n\n   *   **Save as Default:** After customizing all the styles you want, go to `Format` > `Paragraph styles` > `Options` > `Save as my default styles`. This saves your formatting preferences for future documents.\n\n**2. Changing the \"Normal Text\" Default:**\n\n   *  **Format Text:** Type some text and format it to your desired default font, size, color, etc.\n   *  **Update Normal Text Style:** Go to `Format` > `Paragraph styles` > `Normal text` > `Update Normal text to match`.\n   *  **Save as Default:** Go to `Format` > `Paragraph styles` > `Options` > `Save as my default styles`.\n\n**3. Using Templates:**\n\n   *   Create a document with all your desired title, heading, and body text formatting.  This includes setting paragraph spacing, margins, headers/footers, etc.\n   *   Go to `File` > `Save as template`.  You can save it as a personal template.\n   *   When you need a new document, go to `File` > `New` > `From template` and select your custom template.\n\n**4. Browser Default Font (Less Precise):**\n\n   While not ideal for Google Docs specifically, you can influence the *base* font to some extent by changing your browser's default font settings.  However, this is a less reliable approach because Google Docs will still use its own styles if they're applied, and this won't affect the default styling of Titles, Headings, etc.\n\n**5. Add-ons (Limited Usefulness):**\n\n   There are some Google Docs add-ons that claim to help with formatting, but they often add complexity and may not be the most reliable solution. I would recommend using the built-in methods first.\n\n**Key Considerations:**\n\n*   **Scope:**  Modifying styles applies to that specific document unless you save them as your default styles (as described above).\n\n*   **Inheritance:**  Styles like `Heading 1` are often based on the `Normal text` style.  So, changing `Normal text` can have a cascading effect on other styles.  This can be good or bad, depending on your intent.\n\n*   **Consistency:**  The primary advantage of using styles is to maintain consistency across your documents.  Avoid manually formatting each heading individually.\n\n*   **Clear Formatting (Optional but recommended):**  If you have a document with inconsistent formatting, you can try \"Clear formatting\" (select text, then `Format` > `Clear formatting`) before applying the desired styles.  This removes any local formatting overrides and makes it easier to get consistent results.\n\nBy using the \"Modify Default Styles\" method, you can effectively customize the appearance of titles, headings, and body text in your Google Docs and ensure a professional, consistent look for all your documents.\n",
